.TH KAL 1 "May 2026" "Linux User's Manual" "General Commands Manual"
.SH NAME
kal \- a lightweight, stateful, Unix-philosophical calendar filter
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B kal
[\fB\-v\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B kal
is a stream-oriented calendar utility that reads a user's calendar entries from
.I ~/.kalendar
and prints events that match the current system date context to standard output. 
Following strict Unix philosophy, it allocates no internal event buffers, acting 
as a pure pipeline filter. Advanced operations like chronological sorting, priority 
organization, and tag filtering are intended to be handled downstream via standard 
system utilities like
.BR sort (1)
and
.BR grep (1).
.PP
The calendar header displaying the current date context is explicitly routed to standard error
.RI ( stderr )
to ensure that pipelining standard output to other text manipulation tools remains entirely clean.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-v
Verbose mode. Prints a confirmation message to standard error upon successfully loading the 
calendar file, and outputs text file comments exactly as they appear in the file stream.
.SH FILE FORMAT
The 
.I ~/.kalendar
file is processed line-by-line. Empty lines are ignored.
.TP
.B Comment Lines
Lines beginning with a hash mark (\fB#\fR) are treated as comments. They are normally 
silently skipped unless the verbose flag (\fB\-v\fR) is enabled.
.TP
.B Event Lines
Standard entries must consist of a date or conditional designator string, followed 
immediately by a literal tab character (\fB\\t\fR), followed by the event payload text. 
Any trailing spaces or extra tabs on the designator side are automatically sanitized 
and stripped before evaluation. Lines missing a tab delimiter are rejected.
.TP
.B Continuation Lines
Lines beginning with a literal tab character (\fB\\t\fR) act as continuation elements. 
They inherit the designator condition parsed from the most recent valid event line.
.SH DESIGNATOR SYNTAX
The designator component matches the current system date using the following variations (all textual matches are case-insensitive):
.TP
.B *
Global daily wildcard. Matches every single day.
.TP
.BI MMM " *"
Textual month wildcard (e.g., \fBmay *\fR, \fBSeptember *\fR). Matches every day of that month. Supports 3-letter, 4-letter (\fBsept\fR), and full month names.
.TP
.BI M " *" \fR, \fBMI/*\fR, \fBMI-*\fR
Numeric month wildcards (e.g., \fB5 *\fR, \fB5/*\fR, \fB5-*\fR). Matches every day of that numeric month (1\-12).
.TP
.BI MMM " DD"
Exact textual date match (e.g., \fBmay 25\fR, \fBJan 01\fR).
.TP
.BI M " DD" \fR, \fBMI/DD\fR, \fBMI-DD\fR
Exact numeric date matrices (e.g., \fB5 25\fR, \fB5/25\fR, \fB5-25\fR).
.TP
.BI MMM " DD " YYYY\fR, \fBMMM " DD, " YYYY
Year-bound absolute dates (e.g., \fBmay 25 2026\fR, \fBmay 25, 2026\fR). Strictly filters out matches if the system clock does not match the specified year.
.TP
.B sun\fR, \fBmonday\fR, \fBtue\fR, ...
Day-of-week shorthand or full name matches. Fires selectively depending on the current day.
.TP
.B weekday\fR, \fBweekend\fR
Macro blocks matching Monday through Friday, or Saturday and Sunday respectively.
.TP
.BI Xth " WDAY"
Relative ordinal weekday occurrences (e.g., \fB4th mon\fR, \fB4th monday\fR). Calculates the relative occurrence week of the current month.
.TP
.B new moon\fR, \fBfull moon\fR
Lunar phase markers. Employs an inline Conway-influenced synodic calculation window (\(+-1 day tolerance) to match current astronomical states.
.SH EXAMPLES
Display today's events:
.EX
.IP "" 4
$ kal
.EE
.PP
Sort today's scheduled events chronologically by passing output to standard sort:
.EX
.IP "" 4
$ kal | sort
.EE
.PP
Filter out high-priority tasks from the day's timeline:
.EX
.IP "" 4
$ kal | sort | grep "PRIORITY_A"
.EE
.SH FILES
.I ~/.kalendar
.RS
The default calendar database file containing tab-delimited designators and events.
.SH DIAGNOSTICS
Exits 0 on success. Exits 1 if the \fBHOME\fR environment variable is missing or if the 
.I ~/.kalendar
file cannot be opened.
